Coupling was demonstrated with an isolated complex from Methanothermobacter wolfeii. The crystal structure of the complex from M. thermolithotrophicus was determined.
FBEB activity was exhibited by the reconstituted enzyme complex after heterologous expression of the encoding genes in E. coli.
The reconstituted enzyme complex catalyzed this reaction at a low rate.
The complex was purified from Geobacter metallireducens. Partial activities, including 1,5-dienoyl-CoA:viologen and diaphorase activities, were characterized.

Interaction with and electron transfer to APS reductase (AprAB) was demonstrated in studies with Desulfovibrio desulfuricans ATCC 2774. The full FBEC reaction is a proposed mechanism based on thermodynamics and genetic evidence.

The sHdrA subunit from H. denitrificans was recombinantly expressed and characterized biochemically and structurally. The full complex was purified from Aquifex aeolicus. The overall reaction is a model based on these experimental data.

The complex was isolated and characterized. It exhibited NAD-specific diaphorase activity, and methylene-H4F reduction was observed with artificial electron donors (reduced benzyl viologen). The full FBEB reaction is a strong proposal based on these findings.

The role of the complex was investigated through gene disruption experiments and comparative transcriptome analysis. Direct biochemical activity of the purified complex for this specific reaction is not described in the text.
